"Kirkstead, Lincolnshire, England":"Kirkstead, Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"um 1046–":"about 1046–Deceased","1046–Female":"1046–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1037–1100":"1037–1100","1064–1130":"1064–1130","1064–Male":"1064–Deceased","1020–1086":"1020–1086","ABT 1064":"about 1064","1037":"1037","1046":"1046","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","um 1046":"about 1046","1064":"1064","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","Kesteven, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Kyme, Lincolnshire, England":"Kyme, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Kirkstead, Lincolnshire, England":"Kirkstead, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rose","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Ostensibly from the vocabulary word denoting the flower (Latin <i>rosa</i>). However, the name was in use throughout the Middle Ages, long before any of the other girls' names derived from flowers, which are generally of 19th-century origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":20,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":40,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":50,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Rose de Danifer was born about 1046, in Kirkstead, Lincolnshire, England as the daughter of Rafin of Lincolnshire and Mrs Rafin of Lincolnshire. She had at least 2 sons with Sir Simon de Kyme."},"et":{"um 1046–":"umbes 1046–Surnud","1046–Female":"10